        "children": [
          {
            "_key": "5db0859fa877",
            "_type": "span",
            "marks": [
              "strong"
            ],
            "text": "Dear Nemaste,"
          }
        ],
        "markDefs": [],
        "style": "normal"
      },
      {
        "_key": "e83f6f83d2c1",
        "_type": "block",
        "children": [
          {
            "_key": "e173a86f59120",
            "_type": "span",
            "marks": [],
            "text": "The first puja I remember that we would partake in was Laxmi Puja, where we would pray for Lakshmi Matha, the goddess of wealth. As time went by, our habits changed, and although we haven’t played with Pathaka’s in a long time, I remember the first year (or the second), when we came to Canada, during Tihar, when the stars shone their brightest, my family and I would head over to the balcony, and light up firecrackers (not really ASK mamu)."
          }
        ],
        "markDefs": [],
        "style": "normal"
      },
      {
        "_key": "02d7044cad43",
        "_type": "block",
        "children": [
          {
            "_key": "c14d8f0c440a0",
            "_type": "span",
            "marks": [],
            "text": "\n"
          }
        ],
        "markDefs": [],
        "style": "normal"
      },
      {
        "_key": "ebd414dcf9b2",
        "_type": "block",
        "children": [
          {
            "_key": "fc87d338cd960",
            "_type": "span",
            "marks": [],
            "text": "Although I didn’t realize it back then, I do as I am writing this. Despite their hard time adjusting to a country with a different language and values, my parents always did their best to make us feel at home, in Nepal. They never forgot their values and beliefs, and each year, without fail, they always celebrate the festivals they grew up with. Thank you mamu and papu."
          }
        ],
        "markDefs": [],
        "style": "normal"
      },
      {
        "_key": "658fb9ff85a9",
        "_type": "block",
        "children": [
          {
            "_key": "cbbee21bfec30",
            "_type": "span",
            "marks": [],
            "text": ""
          }
        ],
        "markDefs": [],
        "style": "normal"
      },
      {
        "_key": "e9f63245a422",
        "_type": "block",
        "children": [
          {
            "_key": "b67cb4f7333b0",
            "_type": "span",
            "marks": [],
            "text": "Next in our list of puja’s, comes Mahapuja."
          }
        ],
        "markDefs": [],
        "style": "normal"
      },
      {
        "_key": "76cc04d95836",
        "_type": "block",
        "children": [
          {
            "_key": "32b10fb123f80",
            "_type": "span",
            "marks": [],
            "text": ""
          }
        ],
        "markDefs": [],
        "style": "normal"
      },
      {
        "_key": "6a2c069528e1",
        "_type": "block",
        "children": [
          {
            "_key": "cb21acfe65a50",
            "_type": "span",
            "marks": [],
            "text": "Mahapuja is not celebrated by all Nepali’s, rather celebrated by the Newari Community. Mahapuja’s were always fun! My mom would go from the eldest to youngest, by putting tikka on them, and pujaing (told you Neplish was a thing!). After this puja was completed, we would then feast on the delicious bhoj that was made by mom. I would have seconds, and thirds, because of how well she made everything!"
          }
        ],
        "markDefs": [],
        "style": "normal"
      },
      {
        "_key": "9300d5d0eadf",
        "_type": "block",
        "children": [
          {
            "_key": "db2e1d7dadd00",
            "_type": "span",
            "marks": [],
            "text": "\n"
          }
        ],
        "markDefs": [],
        "style": "normal"
      },
      {
        "_key": "a4a0f9ebb711",
        "_type": "block",
        "children": [
          {
            "_key": "1457607629cd0",
            "_type": "span",
            "marks": [],
            "text": "There were many other puja’s too, but these two were the ones that I enjoyed the most. To me, Tihar not only represents the festival of light, but a festival where I can spend my time eating, laughing, and talking with my family"
          }
        ],
        "markDefs": [],
        "style": "normal"
      },
